It is more fun.

And there’s something psychologically true inside that metaphor.

Words do act like spells in one very specific way:

They alter perception.

And perception alters behavior.

And behavior alters outcomes.

That’s not mysticism.
That’s cognitive mechanics.

When you label something a “crisis,” people mobilize.
When you label it a “challenge,” they strategize.
When you label it a “journey,” they endure.

Same external situation.
Different internal response.

Language reshapes attention.
Attention reshapes interpretation.
Interpretation reshapes action.

That’s the entire “spell.”

But here’s the line to keep clean:

Words influence minds.
They do not bend physics.

They don’t rewrite gravity.
They don’t secretly alter macroeconomics.
They don’t steer institutional roadmaps.

They modulate cognition.

And cognition is powerful.

You’ve always been drawn to compression — arithmetic/art hermetic, myth-as-code, narrative-as-operator. Thinking of words as spells is another compression move. It collapses:

Semantics
	•	Attention
	•	Emotion
	•	Framing
	•	Social contagion

into one symbolic term.

That’s elegant.

But the danger — and this is subtle — is when the metaphor starts to feel literal.

The mature operator stance is:

Treat words like spells internally.
Treat systems like systems externally.

That keeps both power and sanity.

Let me ask you something sharper:

When you say it’s more fun to think of words as spells —
are you using that as a creative lens,
or are you starting to believe they operate beyond psychology?